    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2397238650" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2397238650" />
    <a title="Javier" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82945-javier"><img alt="Javier" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563838722p2/82945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2397238650?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Javier" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Javier" href="/user/show/82945-javier">Javier</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=europe">europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=ethics">ethics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=revolution">revolution</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=anarchism">anarchism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/82945-javier?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2397238650" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13488633184280786733">Though dry and repetitious at times, this is overall an excellent volume. I can see very definite echoes of this text in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7084.Karl_Marx' title='Karl Marx' rel='nofollow noopener'>Karl Marx</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5258928.Mikhail_Bakunin' title='Mikhail Bakunin' rel='nofollow noopener'>Mikhail Bakunin</a>&apos;s writings and life-work. One can&apos;t forget the &quot;Theses on Feuerbach.&quot; It&apos;s clear how this work (from 1841) inspired an entire generation of European radicals, in the sense of calling for heaven on Earth rather than postponing it indefinitely until an uncertain afterlife, as institutional Christianity suggests (then as now). In this sense, I saw a </span>
  <span id="freeText13488633184280786733" style="display:none">Though dry and repetitious at times, this is overall an excellent volume. I can see very definite echoes of this text in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7084.Karl_Marx" title="Karl Marx" rel="nofollow noopener">Karl Marx</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5258928.Mikhail_Bakunin" title="Mikhail Bakunin" rel="nofollow noopener">Mikhail Bakunin</a>'s writings and life-work. One can't forget the "Theses on Feuerbach." It's clear how this work (from 1841) inspired an entire generation of European radicals, in the sense of calling for heaven on Earth rather than postponing it indefinitely until an uncertain afterlife, as institutional Christianity suggests (then as now). In this sense, I saw a clear parallel with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/658.The_Kingdom_of_God_Is_Within_You" title="The Kingdom of God Is Within You by Leo Tolstoy" rel="nofollow noopener">The Kingdom of God Is Within You</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/128382.Leo_Tolstoy" title="Leo Tolstoy" rel="nofollow noopener">Leo Tolstoy</a>. Feuerbach's concluding chapters on the conflict between faith (which is particular, narrow, and hierarchical) and love (which, like reason, is free, universal, and all-embracing) parallel Tolstoy's discussion of the distinction between institutional Christianity (or any organized religion, really) and the revolutionary message of Jesus the Nazarene:<br /><br />"It was faith, not love, not reason, which invented Hell. To love, Hell is a horror; to reason, an absurdity, an absurdity" (p. 257).<br /><br />"True love is sufficient to itself; it needs no special title, no authority. Love is the universal law of intelligence and Nature;—it is nothing else than the realisation of the unity of the species through the medium of moral sentiment" (p. 266).<br /><br />"All love founded on a special historical phenomenon contradicts [...] the nature of love, which endures no limits, which triumphs over all particularity. Man [<i>sic</i>] is to be loved for man's sake. Man is an object of love because he is an end in himself, because he is a rational and loving being. This is the law of the species, the law of the intelligence" (p. 268)<br /><br />And in the conclusion, Feuerbach sets forth this alternative: "the highest and first law must be the love of man to man. <i>Homo homini Deus est</i> [man {<i>sic</i>} is a god to man]: this is the great practical principle: this is the axis on which revolves the history of the world" (p. 271).<br /><br />And lastly, how about this, from the book's closing paragraph?<br /><br />"Hunger and thirst destroy not only the physical but also the mental and moral powers of man [<i>sic</i>]; they rob him of his humanity—of understanding, of consciousness. Oh! if thou shouldst ever experience such want, how wouldst thou bless and praise the natural qualities of bread and wine, which restore to thee thy humanity, thy intellect! <b>It needs only that the ordinary course of things be interrupted</b> in order to vindicate to common things an uncommon significance, <i>to life, as such, a religious import"</i> (p. 278-9).</span>
  <a data-text-id="13488633184280786733" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

